<h2>%%ReferenceStyle%%Book, one source quoted in another</h2>
<hr>
<br>
Avoid where possible!
<br>
<br>
It is better to refer back to the original source yourself so you can check the accuracy of the 
quoted material. If the original source is unavailable, use <strong>&#8216;as cited in&#8217;</strong> 
in your text. The original authors, and year if known, are named in your text, but only the source you 
actually read goes in the reference list. For example, if a study by Jones and Chan was quoted in a 
work that you read by Smith, you would only list Smith in your reference list.
<br>
<br>
<strong>REFERENCE LIST ENTRY</strong>
<br>
<br>
<strong>Format</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="ref-hang-indent double-line-spacing">
	Author(s). (Year of publication). <em>Title of book (that you read)</em>. 
	Publisher.
</blockquote>
<br>
<strong>Example</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="ref-hang-indent double-line-spacing">
	<span class="hover" title="Author(s)">Smith, A. R.</span> 
	(<span class="hover" title="Year of publication">2017</span>). 
	<em><span class="hover" title="Title of book (that you read)">Teaching and learning in higher education</span></em>. 
	<span class="hover" title="Publisher">University Books</span>.
</blockquote>
<br>
