<hr>
<br>
<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br>
<br>
Name the original authors, and year if known, and use &#8216;as cited in&#8217; to refer to the 
secondary work you read. For example, a study by Jones and Chan was quoted in a work by Smith, but 
you did not read the study by Jones and Chan.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	A recent study (Jones &amp; Chan, 2015, as cited in Smith, 2017) showed &hellip;
	<br>
	Alternatively: Webber and Reed (2010, as cited in Smith, 2017) indicated that&hellip;
</blockquote>
<br>
If you are using a direct quotation, consisting of fewer than 40 words, enclose the quote using double 
quotation marks and include page numbers.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Webber and Reed (as cited in Smith, 2017) observed that &#34;students perform better when rested&#34; 
	(p. 56).
	<br>
	Alternatively: Therefore, &#34;students perform better when rested&#34; (Jones &amp; Chan, 2015, as 
	cited in Smith, 2017, p. 56).
</blockquote>
<br>
If the quotation is greater than 40 words, the quote is displayed in a double spaced, indented 
block at 1.27cm from the left margin. Do not use double quotation marks to enclose a block quotation.
